-- Targeted migration: standardize Cisco CCNP ENCOR 350-401-P1/P2 to spec.
-- 1) Bump questionCount to 100 (official 90-110 midpoint).
-- 2) Insert 37 grounded fill questions across 5 under-served ENCOR domains.
-- Does NOT touch published or deletedAt on any row.
-- Idempotent: UPDATEs filter on current value; INSERTs guarded by WHERE NOT EXISTS.

CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pgcrypto;

-- 1) Standardize questionCount
UPDATE "Exam" SET "questionCount" = 100
  WHERE code IN ('350-401-P1', '350-401-P2') AND "questionCount" <> 100;

-- 2) Insert grounded fill questions
-- 350-401-P1: 26 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network architect is designing a large enterprise campus network that must support thousands of endpoints across multiple buildings. The design requires clear separation between the access layer, a distribution layer for policy enforcement, and a high-speed backbone. Which campus architecture model BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Two-tier (collapsed core) architecture"},{"id":"b","text":"Three-tier (access, distribution, core) architecture"},{"id":"c","text":"Single-tier flat architecture"},{"id":"d","text":"SD-Access fabric architecture without any physical tiering"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Three-tier (campus): access -> distribution -> core; large enterprise.' This model explicitly provides three distinct layers — access for endpoint connectivity, distribution for policy enforcement and aggregation, and core for high-speed backbone forwarding — making it the correct choice for a large enterprise campus. The two-tier (collapsed core) model merges distribution and core, which is suited for smaller networks, not large enterprises with thousands of endpoints. A single-tier flat architecture lacks scalability and policy enforcement boundaries. SD-Access is an overlay fabric technology but does not replace the need for physical tiering in a traditional campus design context.$patch$, $patch$Architecture$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/encor-exam-topics","label":"Cisco ENCOR 350-401 Official Cert Guide – Campus Network Design"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/solutions/Enterprise/Campus/campover.html","label":"Cisco Design Zone – Campus LAN Design Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network architect is designing a large enterprise campus network that must support thousands of endpoints across multiple buildings. The design requires clear separation between the access layer, a distribution layer for policy enforcement, and a high-speed backbone. Which campus architecture model BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In a Cisco SD-WAN (Viptela) deployment, a network engineer needs to identify which component is responsible for distributing routing and policy information (OMP routes) to all vEdge/cEdge routers in the overlay fabric. Which SD-WAN component fulfills this role?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"vBond"},{"id":"b","text":"vManage"},{"id":"c","text":"vSmart"},{"id":"d","text":"cEdge"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material identifies the Cisco SD-WAN components as: 'vManage (orchestration), vSmart (control), vBond (orchestrator/zero-touch), vEdge/cEdge routers.' The vSmart controller is the control-plane component that runs the Overlay Management Protocol (OMP) and distributes routing information, policies, and crypto key material to all WAN edge devices. vManage is the centralized management and orchestration GUI. vBond handles initial authentication and zero-touch provisioning of edge devices. cEdge/vEdge routers are the data-plane forwarding devices. Therefore, vSmart is the correct answer for control-plane (routing/policy) distribution.$patch$, $patch$Architecture$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/routers/sdwan/configuration/sdwan-xe-gs-book/system-overview.html","label":"Cisco SD-WAN Design Guide – Controller Functional Overview"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/encor-exam-topics","label":"Cisco ENCOR 350-401 Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In a Cisco SD-WAN (Viptela) deployment, a network engineer needs to identify which component is responsible for distributing routing and policy information (OMP routes) to all vEdge/cEdge routers in the overlay fabric. Which SD-WAN component fulfills this role?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An enterprise is deploying Cisco SD-Access. The network architect states that the underlay network uses a specific routing protocol and the overlay uses LISP for control-plane functions with VXLAN for data-plane encapsulation. Which routing protocol does the SD-Access underlay use by default, and which protocol handles host-mobility control-plane functions in the overlay?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Underlay: OSPF; Overlay control-plane: BGP EVPN"},{"id":"b","text":"Underlay: IS-IS (routed); Overlay control-plane: LISP"},{"id":"c","text":"Underlay: EIGRP; Overlay control-plane: VXLAN"},{"id":"d","text":"Underlay: BGP; Overlay control-plane: GRE"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'SD-Access / Cisco DNA: fabric architecture with underlay (routed IS-IS) + overlay (LISP/VXLAN), separation of control/data plane via LISP, GRE/VXLAN encapsulation.' IS-IS is the default underlay routing protocol used by Cisco DNA Center to automate the routed access design. LISP (Locator/ID Separation Protocol) provides the control-plane for endpoint location and mobility tracking in the overlay, while VXLAN provides the data-plane encapsulation. OSPF, EIGRP, BGP, BGP EVPN, and GRE are not the default SD-Access underlay/overlay combination as described in the source material.$patch$, $patch$Architecture$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/solutions/CVD/Campus/cisco-sda-design-guide.html","label":"Cisco SD-Access Solution Design Guide – Fabric Overlay and Underlay"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/docs/dna-center/#!sd-access-overview","label":"Cisco DNA Center SD-Access Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An enterprise is deploying Cisco SD-Access. The network architect states that the underlay network uses a specific routing protocol and the overlay uses LISP for control-plane functions with VXLAN for data-plane encapsulation. Which routing protocol does the SD-Access underlay use by default, and which protocol handles host-mobility control-plane functions in the overlay?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is configuring a first-hop redundancy protocol on a distribution layer switch pair. The requirement states that the solution must support active load balancing of traffic across both gateway routers simultaneously using a single virtual IP address and a single virtual MAC address. Which FHRP should the engineer implement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"HSRP version 1"},{"id":"b","text":"VRRP version 3"},{"id":"c","text":"GLBP"},{"id":"d","text":"HSRP version 2"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'GLBP (Cisco proprietary, supports load balancing across AVF).' GLBP (Gateway Load Balancing Protocol) is the only FHRP that provides true active/active load balancing. It uses a single virtual IP address while multiple Active Virtual Forwarders (AVFs) each have their own virtual MAC address, distributing host traffic across all gateways simultaneously. HSRP (both v1 and v2) uses an active/standby model where only one router forwards traffic at a time — the standby router is idle until failover. VRRP similarly uses a master/backup model with only one active forwarder. Neither HSRP nor VRRP natively load-balances across both routers without additional per-VLAN/group tricks.$patch$, $patch$Architecture$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipapp_fhrp/configuration/xe-16/fhp-xe-16-book/fhp-glbp.html","label":"Cisco IOS Gateway Load Balancing Protocol (GLBP) Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/hot-standby-router-protocol-hsrp/9234-hsrpglbp.html","label":"Cisco FHRP Comparison – HSRP, VRRP, GLBP"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is configuring a first-hop redundancy protocol on a distribution layer switch pair. The requirement states that the solution must support active load balancing of traffic across both gateway routers simultaneously using a single virtual IP address and a single virtual MAC address. Which FHRP should the engineer implement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A wireless engineer is deploying access points in a remote branch office that has limited WAN bandwidth to the central data center. The design requires that client data traffic be switched locally at the branch and only management/control traffic traverse the WAN to the Wireless LAN Controller. Which AP operational mode should be configured to meet this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Local mode"},{"id":"b","text":"Monitor mode"},{"id":"c","text":"FlexConnect mode"},{"id":"d","text":"Sniffer mode"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material describes AP modes as follows: 'Local (default, traffic tunneled to WLC via CAPWAP)' and 'FlexConnect (local switching).' FlexConnect (formerly H-REAP) is specifically designed for branch office deployments where the AP can switch client data traffic locally at the branch without hairpinning it across the WAN to the WLC. Only control and management traffic uses the CAPWAP tunnel to the central WLC, conserving WAN bandwidth. Local mode tunnels ALL client data via CAPWAP to the WLC, which would consume significant WAN bandwidth — the opposite of what is required. Monitor mode is used for passive RF monitoring and does not serve clients. Sniffer mode captures 802.11 frames and forwards them to a packet analyzer — it also does not serve clients.$patch$, $patch$Architecture$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/wireless/controller/technotes/flexconnect-dg.html","label":"Cisco FlexConnect Design and Deployment Guide"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/wireless/catalyst-9800-series-wireless-controllers/213485-catalyst-9800-ap-modes-overview.html","label":"Cisco Wireless LAN Controller AP Modes – Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A wireless engineer is deploying access points in a remote branch office that has limited WAN bandwidth to the central data center. The design requires that client data traffic be switched locally at the branch and only management/control traffic traverse the WAN to the Wireless LAN Controller. Which AP operational mode should be configured to meet this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is designing a data center fabric that requires Layer 2 extension across Layer 3 boundaries and must support approximately 10 million logical network segments. Which encapsulation technology best satisfies both requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"GRE (Generic Routing Encapsulation)"},{"id":"b","text":"VXLAN (Virtual Extensible LAN)"},{"id":"c","text":"IPsec in transport mode"},{"id":"d","text":"802.1Q VLAN trunking"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that VXLAN uses MAC-in-UDP encapsulation and provides a 24-bit VNI (Virtual Network Identifier), which yields up to 16 million logical segments — far exceeding the 4,094 limit of 802.1Q VLANs. VXLAN is explicitly noted as used for DC fabric and SD-Access overlays, making it the correct choice. GRE is a simpler IP-in-IP tunnel that carries no segment identifier at this scale. IPsec transport mode encrypts the payload between two endpoints but does not provide multi-tenancy segmentation identifiers. 802.1Q is limited to 4,094 VLANs and cannot span Layer 3 boundaries natively.$patch$, $patch$Virtualization$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/collateral/switches/nexus-9000-series-switches/white-paper-c11-729383.html","label":"Cisco VXLAN Overview – Cisco Documentation"},{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7348","label":"RFC 7348 – Virtual eXtensible Local Area Network (VXLAN)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is designing a data center fabric that requires Layer 2 extension across Layer 3 boundaries and must support approximately 10 million logical network segments. Which encapsulation technology best satisfies both requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An enterprise is deploying DMVPN to enable dynamic spoke-to-spoke tunnels. After initial deployment in Phase 1, the team upgrades to Phase 3. What is the primary functional enhancement introduced in DMVPN Phase 3 compared to Phase 2?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Phase 3 replaces NHRP entirely with a BGP-based next-hop resolution mechanism."},{"id":"b","text":"Phase 3 uses NHRP Redirect messages to allow spokes to build direct tunnels via a single-hop shortcut, regardless of summarization boundaries."},{"id":"c","text":"Phase 3 introduces IPsec AH authentication to replace ESP encryption on spoke-to-spoke tunnels."},{"id":"d","text":"Phase 3 changes the hub role to a passive reflector that no longer participates in data-plane forwarding."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly lists DMVPN phases: 'phase 1 (hub-spoke), phase 2 (spoke-to-spoke), phase 3 (NHRP redirect).' In Phase 3, the hub sends an NHRP Redirect to the originating spoke, instructing it to build a direct shortcut tunnel to the destination spoke. The key advantage over Phase 2 is that Phase 3 works correctly even when the hub is summarizing routes, because the redirect mechanism decouples next-hop resolution from routing summarization constraints. NHRP is not replaced by BGP (option A is false). IPsec mode selection is independent of DMVPN phase (option C is false). The hub continues to participate in forwarding until the shortcut is established (option D is false).$patch$, $patch$Virtualization$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/solutions/Enterprise/WAN_and_MAN/DMVPN_2_Phase3/DMVPN_Phase3.html","label":"Cisco DMVPN Design Guide – Phase 1, 2, and 3 Explained"},{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc2332","label":"RFC 2332 – NBMA Next Hop Resolution Protocol (NHRP)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An enterprise is deploying DMVPN to enable dynamic spoke-to-spoke tunnels. After initial deployment in Phase 1, the team upgrades to Phase 3. What is the primary functional enhancement introduced in DMVPN Phase 3 compared to Phase 2?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A service provider wants to run multiple customers' routing tables on a single physical router while keeping their traffic completely isolated. The engineer also needs to selectively share specific routes between two customer VRFs. Which combination of VRF features should be used?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"VRF-Lite with VLAN sub-interfaces only; no additional configuration is required for route sharing."},{"id":"b","text":"Multiple VRF instances for isolation, with route-target import/export configured for route leaking between the desired VRFs."},{"id":"c","text":"A single global routing table partitioned by administrative distance values to separate customer routes."},{"id":"d","text":"GRE tunnels between each customer VRF with static routes to achieve selective route sharing."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'VRF: Multiple routing tables on the same device; route leaking via route-target import/export. Used for multi-tenancy on a single physical router.' VRF provides the necessary isolation by giving each customer its own routing table instance. Route leaking — the mechanism for selectively sharing routes between VRFs — is accomplished through the route-target import/export extended community attributes in MP-BGP. Option A (VLAN sub-interfaces alone) provides L2 separation but does not create independent routing tables. Option C (administrative distance partitioning) does not isolate routing tables; it only influences path selection within a single table. Option D (GRE tunnels) is an overly complex workaround that does not natively use the VRF construct for leaking.$patch$, $patch$Virtualization$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_bgp/configuration/xe-16/irg-xe-16-book/bgp-mpls-vpns.html","label":"Cisco VRF and Route Leaking Configuration Guide – IOS XE"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccnp-and-ccie-enterprise-core-encor-350-401-official-9780138216764","label":"Cisco ENCOR (350-401) Official Cert Guide – Virtualization Chapter"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A service provider wants to run multiple customers' routing tables on a single physical router while keeping their traffic completely isolated. The engineer also needs to selectively share specific routes between two customer VRFs. Which combination of VRF features should be used?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network architect is evaluating hypervisor options for a new branch virtualization deployment. The security policy mandates that the hypervisor must not rely on an underlying host operating system and must run directly on bare-metal hardware. Which of the following hypervisor products satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"VMware Workstation"},{"id":"b","text":"Oracle VirtualBox"},{"id":"c","text":"VMware ESXi"},{"id":"d","text":"Microsoft Hyper-V running inside Windows 11 Desktop Edition"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines Type 1 hypervisors (bare metal) as those that run directly on hardware without a host OS, listing 'ESXi, KVM, Hyper-V' as examples. Type 2 hypervisors (hosted) require a host OS and are exemplified by 'VMware Workstation, VirtualBox.' VMware ESXi is a Type 1 bare-metal hypervisor and therefore satisfies the security policy. VMware Workstation (option A) and Oracle VirtualBox (option B) are explicitly listed as Type 2 hosted hypervisors and rely on an underlying OS. Hyper-V is a Type 1 hypervisor by architecture, but the question qualifies it as 'running inside Windows 11 Desktop Edition,' which describes the hosted client Hyper-V experience dependent on a general-purpose OS — making option D incorrect in this specific deployment context.$patch$, $patch$Virtualization$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-vSphere/8.0/vsphere-esxi-installation/GUID-B2F01BF5-078A-4C7E-B505-5DFFED0B8C38.html","label":"VMware ESXi Product Overview – VMware Documentation"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/encor-exam-topics","label":"Cisco ENCOR 350-401 Exam Topics – Virtualization (1.0)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network architect is evaluating hypervisor options for a new branch virtualization deployment. The security policy mandates that the hypervisor must not rely on an underlying host operating system and must run directly on bare-metal hardware. Which of the following hypervisor products satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer needs to monitor jitter and packet loss between two branch routers and automatically trigger a routing change when the measured loss exceeds a defined threshold. Which Cisco feature best satisfies both requirements with a single configuration?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Embedded Packet Capture (EPC) with a capture filter on ICMP traffic"},{"id":"b","text":"IP SLA with a track object linked to a static route or HSRP priority"},{"id":"c","text":"SNMPv3 traps sent to a central NMS whenever interface error counters increment"},{"id":"d","text":"Flexible NetFlow (FNF) exporting jitter records to a flow collector"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'IP SLA: active probe configured on a router to measure latency, jitter, loss, reachability; tracks objects can trigger HSRP/EEM/route changes.' IP SLA is the only listed tool that both actively measures jitter and packet loss AND can trigger automated network changes (via track objects tied to static routes or HSRP priority adjustments). EPC is a passive capture tool with no threshold/reaction capability. SNMPv3 traps are reactive notifications from the device OS, not active probes measuring jitter. FNF exports flow telemetry but does not natively measure jitter or trigger routing changes.$patch$, $patch$Network Assurance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipsla/configuration/xe-17/sla-xe-17-book/sla_overview.html","label":"Cisco IP SLA Configuration Guide – Cisco IOS XE"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/encor-exam-topics","label":"Cisco ENCOR 350-401 Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer needs to monitor jitter and packet loss between two branch routers and automatically trigger a routing change when the measured loss exceeds a defined threshold. Which Cisco feature best satisfies both requirements with a single configuration?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization wants to replace frequent SNMP polling of high-frequency interface metrics with a more scalable, push-based collection mechanism that uses YANG data models. Which technology should the network engineer deploy?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"SNMPv2c with a reduced polling interval of 10 seconds"},{"id":"b","text":"NetFlow v9 exported to a dedicated flow collector"},{"id":"c","text":"Model-driven streaming telemetry over gRPC or NETCONF"},{"id":"d","text":"RSPAN mirroring all management traffic to an out-of-band monitoring server"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Streaming telemetry over gRPC/NETCONF (model-driven, push-based, YANG-defined). Replaces SNMP polling for high-frequency metrics.' Model-driven telemetry pushes data from the device to the collector at defined intervals without waiting for a poll request, making it far more scalable for high-frequency metrics. SNMPv2c is pull-based and does not use YANG models; reducing its polling interval worsens scalability. NetFlow v9 provides flow-level data, not per-interface counters, and is not YANG-defined. RSPAN is a packet-mirroring technology unrelated to metric collection.$patch$, $patch$Network Assurance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/prog/configuration/1612/b_1612_programmability_cg/model_driven_telemetry.html","label":"Cisco Model-Driven Telemetry Configuration Guide – IOS XE"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/encor-exam-topics","label":"Cisco ENCOR 350-401 Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization wants to replace frequent SNMP polling of high-frequency interface metrics with a more scalable, push-based collection mechanism that uses YANG data models. Which technology should the network engineer deploy?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security team requires that all SNMP communications between network devices and the NMS be authenticated and encrypted to prevent credential interception on the management network. The team also wants unsolicited event notifications that do NOT require acknowledgment from the NMS. Which combination of SNMP version and notification type meets both requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"SNMPv2c using community strings and SNMP informs"},{"id":"b","text":"SNMPv3 with authPriv security level and SNMP traps"},{"id":"c","text":"SNMPv3 with authPriv security level and SNMP informs"},{"id":"d","text":"SNMPv2c using community strings and SNMP traps"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'SNMPv2c (community string, plaintext) vs SNMPv3 (auth+priv, USM)' and 'Traps (unsolicited) vs informs (acknowledged).' The requirement is for authentication AND encryption (ruling out SNMPv2c, which is plaintext) combined with unsolicited notifications that do NOT require acknowledgment (ruling out informs, which are acknowledged). SNMPv3 with authPriv provides both authentication (auth) and encryption (priv) via USM. Traps are unsolicited and unacknowledged, satisfying the second requirement. Option C uses informs, which are acknowledged — the opposite of what is required. Options A and D use SNMPv2c, which transmits community strings in plaintext.$patch$, $patch$Network Assurance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/snmp/configuration/xe-17/snmp-xe-17-book/nm-snmp-cfg-snmp-support.html","label":"Cisco SNMP Configuration Guide – SNMPv3"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/encor-exam-topics","label":"Cisco ENCOR 350-401 Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security team requires that all SNMP communications between network devices and the NMS be authenticated and encrypted to prevent credential interception on the management network. The team also wants unsolicited event notifications that do NOT require acknowledgment from the NMS. Which combination of SNMP version and notification type meets both requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator needs to capture live packets directly on a Cisco IOS XE router for troubleshooting, without connecting an external packet analyzer to any physical port. The captured traffic must be exportable as a .pcap file for offline analysis. Which Cisco feature should the administrator use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"SPAN (Switched Port Analyzer) configured on the router's uplink interface"},{"id":"b","text":"ERSPAN tunneling the mirrored traffic over GRE to a remote collector"},{"id":"c","text":"Embedded Packet Capture (EPC) storing packets in router memory for export"},{"id":"d","text":"Flexible NetFlow (FNF) with a custom flow record capturing full packet payloads"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'EPC (Embedded Packet Capture) for on-device pcap.' EPC allows a Cisco IOS XE router to capture packets directly in device memory and export them as a standard .pcap file — no external analyzer or additional physical port is required. SPAN mirrors traffic to a physical port and requires an external device connected to that port; it cannot export a .pcap file on its own. ERSPAN encapsulates mirrored traffic in GRE and sends it to a remote IP destination, still requiring an external capture station and a physical or logical destination. FNF records flow-level metadata (5-tuple and statistics) but does not capture full packet payloads or produce .pcap output.$patch$, $patch$Network Assurance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/epc/configuration/xe-17/epc-xe-17-book/nm-packet-capture.html","label":"Cisco Embedded Packet Capture Configuration Guide – IOS XE"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/encor-exam-topics","label":"Cisco ENCOR 350-401 Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
