INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer needs to protect the Route Processor CPU on a Cisco router from high-rate traffic floods originating from the network. Which Cisco IOS feature should be implemented to rate-limit traffic destined to the Route Processor?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Management Plane Protection (MPP)"},{"id":"b","text":"Control Plane Policing (CoPP)"},{"id":"c","text":"Control Plane Protection (CPPr)"},{"id":"d","text":"Cisco TrustSec SGT enforcement"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Control Plane Policing (CoPP) is the correct answer. Per the source material, 'CoPP: rate-limit traffic destined to RP CPU.' CoPP uses a service policy applied to the control plane to police aggregate traffic sent to the Route Processor, protecting it from DoS-style floods. CPPr (option C) is a more granular extension of CoPP that sub-categorizes control-plane traffic; it is a subset feature, not the primary rate-limiting feature described. MPP (option A) restricts which interfaces are allowed to carry management traffic but does not rate-limit control-plane traffic. TrustSec SGTs (option D) are used for micro-segmentation and policy enforcement, not CPU protection.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/qos_copp/configuration/xe-17/qos-copp-xe-17-book/qos-copp-ctrl-plane-plcng.html","label":"Cisco IOS XE Control Plane Policing Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
