INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An enterprise security policy requires that SSH and SNMP management access to core routers must only be accepted on the dedicated out-of-band management interface (GigabitEthernet0/0). All other interfaces must silently drop management traffic. Which Cisco feature enforces this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Control Plane Policing (CoPP)"},{"id":"b","text":"Control Plane Protection (CPPr) with sub-interfaces"},{"id":"c","text":"Management Plane Protection (MPP)"},{"id":"d","text":"802.1X port-based authentication"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Management Plane Protection (MPP) is correct. The source material states that MPP is used to 'restrict management traffic to specific interfaces.' By configuring MPP, an administrator designates one or more interfaces as management interfaces; all management protocols (SSH, SNMP, Telnet, etc.) are then rejected on non-designated interfaces. CoPP (option A) can rate-limit management traffic in aggregate but cannot restrict it to a single interface. CPPr (option B) provides sub-categorization of control-plane traffic, not interface-level management restriction. 802.1X (option D) is an access-layer authentication mechanism and is unrelated to restricting management plane access to specific router interfaces.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_mpp/configuration/xe-17/sec-data-mpp-xe-17-book/sec-mpp.html","label":"Cisco IOS XE Management Plane Protection Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An enterprise security policy requires that SSH and SNMP management access to core routers must only be accepted on the dedicated out-of-band management interface (GigabitEthernet0/0). All other interfaces must silently drop management traffic. Which Cisco feature enforces this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security architect is comparing TACACS+ and RADIUS for device administration AAA. Which statement correctly distinguishes TACACS+ from RADIUS?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"TACACS+ uses UDP port 1812 and encrypts only the password field in its packets."},{"id":"b","text":"TACACS+ uses TCP port 49 and encrypts the entire payload, supporting per-command authorization."},{"id":"c","text":"RADIUS uses TCP port 49 and encrypts the entire payload for stronger security."},{"id":"d","text":"RADIUS uses TCP and natively supports command-by-command authorization for network devices."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is correct. The source material explicitly states: 'TACACS+ (TCP/49, encrypts whole payload, command authorization) vs RADIUS (UDP/1812/1813, encrypts only password).' TACACS+ separates Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting into distinct functions and uses TCP port 49 with full-payload encryption, making it the preferred protocol for device administration where per-command authorization is required. Option A incorrectly attributes UDP/1812 and password-only encryption to TACACS+ — those are RADIUS characteristics. Option C incorrectly states RADIUS uses TCP/49 and full-payload encryption. Option D is incorrect because RADIUS does not natively support per-command authorization; that is a TACACS+ capability.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security-vpn/remote-authentication-dial-user-service-radius/13838-10.html","label":"Cisco TACACS+ and RADIUS Comparison"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security architect is comparing TACACS+ and RADIUS for device administration AAA. Which statement correctly distinguishes TACACS+ from RADIUS?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In an 802.1X deployment, a network printer that does not support an 802.1X supplicant must still gain controlled port access. Which mechanism should the network engineer configure on the authenticator switch to handle this device?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"EAP-TLS mutual certificate authentication"},{"id":"b","text":"PEAP with MSCHAPv2 username/password"},{"id":"c","text":"MAC Authentication Bypass (MAB)"},{"id":"d","text":"SXP peer session to a TrustSec-capable switch"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$MAC Authentication Bypass (MAB) is correct. The source material states: 'MAB (MAC Authentication Bypass) for non-802.1X devices.' When a device cannot respond to EAP Identity Requests (as a printer typically cannot), the switch can fall back to MAB, which uses the device's MAC address as both the username and password submitted to the RADIUS server for authentication. EAP-TLS (option A) and PEAP (option B) require the supplicant to actively participate in an EAP exchange, which the printer cannot do. SXP (option D) is a TrustSec protocol for propagating Security Group Tags between devices and is not an authentication fallback mechanism for non-802.1X clients.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/collateral/ios-nx-os-software/identity-based-networking-services/config_guide_c17-663759.html","label":"Cisco MAC Authentication Bypass Deployment Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In an 802.1X deployment, a network printer that does not support an 802.1X supplicant must still gain controlled port access. Which mechanism should the network engineer configure on the authenticator switch to handle this device?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A large enterprise wants to deploy micro-segmentation across its campus network so that users in a 'Finance' group are denied access to servers in a 'Development' group, regardless of VLAN or IP addressing. The solution must scale without requiring per-device ACLs. Which Cisco technology best satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Control Plane Policing (CoPP) with aggregate traffic policies"},{"id":"b","text":"Cisco TrustSec with Security Group Tags (SGTs)"},{"id":"c","text":"WPA3 Opportunistic Wireless Encryption (OWE)"},{"id":"d","text":"DMVPN with IPsec tunnel encryption per branch"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Cisco TrustSec with Security Group Tags (SGTs) is correct. The source material states: 'Cisco TrustSec: SGT (Security Group Tags), SXP propagation, micro-segmentation.' TrustSec assigns a numerical SGT to users/devices upon authentication; Security Group ACLs (SGACLs) enforce policy based on source and destination SGTs rather than IP addresses or VLANs, enabling scalable micro-segmentation. CoPP (option A) protects the router CPU and cannot enforce user-group segmentation. OWE (option C) is a WPA3 feature providing encryption for open wireless networks and is irrelevant to LAN segmentation. DMVPN (option D) provides WAN branch connectivity and does not address intra-campus micro-segmentation.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/solutions/Enterprise/Security/TrustSec_1-99/TrustSec_HowTo/TrustSec_HowTo.html","label":"Cisco TrustSec How-To Guide: Deploying SGTs"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A large enterprise wants to deploy micro-segmentation across its campus network so that users in a 'Finance' group are denied access to servers in a 'Development' group, regardless of VLAN or IP addressing. The solution must scale without requiring per-device ACLs. Which Cisco technology best satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A wireless network engineer is upgrading a corporate guest Wi-Fi network from WPA2-Personal to WPA3. Users on the guest network should not be able to decrypt each other's traffic even if they share the same network password. Which WPA3 feature specifically provides this individualized encryption on an open or PSK-style network?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"WPA3-Enterprise 192-bit security suite"},{"id":"b","text":"WPA3 Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)"},{"id":"c","text":"WPA3 Opportunistic Wireless Encryption (OWE)"},{"id":"d","text":"AES-CCMP with 802.1X EAP-TLS authentication"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Opportunistic Wireless Encryption (OWE) is correct. The source material lists WPA3 features as: 'SAE replaces PSK, OWE for open networks, 192-bit suite for enterprise.' OWE (defined in RFC 8110) provides unauthenticated encryption for open-style networks — each client negotiates a unique pairwise encryption key via a Diffie-Hellman exchange, so one client cannot decrypt another's traffic even without a passphrase. SAE (option B) is the WPA3 replacement for the PSK handshake, providing forward secrecy for password-based authentication, but its primary purpose is resisting offline dictionary attacks, not per-client isolation. The 192-bit suite (option A) is for high-security enterprise environments using 802.1X. AES-CCMP with EAP-TLS (option D) is WPA2-Enterprise and does not apply to a guest/open scenario.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.wi-fi.org/discover-wi-fi/security","label":"Wi-Fi Alliance WPA3 Specification Overview"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8110","label":"RFC 8110 – Opportunistic Wireless Encryption"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A wireless network engineer is upgrading a corporate guest Wi-Fi network from WPA2-Personal to WPA3. Users on the guest network should not be able to decrypt each other's traffic even if they share the same network password. Which WPA3 feature specifically provides this individualized encryption on an open or PSK-style network?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An enterprise security team needs a VPN solution for connecting multiple branch offices over a private MPLS WAN. The solution must preserve IP multicast routing across all sites and avoid the overhead of a hub-and-spoke design. Which Cisco VPN technology is specifically designed for this use case?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Remote-access SSL VPN using AnyConnect"},{"id":"b","text":"DMVPN Phase 3 with IPsec profile"},{"id":"c","text":"Group Encrypted Transport VPN (GETVPN)"},{"id":"d","text":"IKEv2 route-based site-to-site IPsec with VTIs"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Group Encrypted Transport VPN (GETVPN) is correct. The source material explicitly states: 'GETVPN (Group Encrypted Transport): for private MPLS, preserves multicast.' GETVPN is a tunnel-less, any-any encryption technology that uses a Group Domain of Interpretation (GDOI) key server; because it does not encapsulate packets in a new IP header, the original source and destination addresses are preserved, enabling native multicast and broadcast forwarding across the MPLS fabric. AnyConnect SSL VPN (option A) is a remote-access solution for individual users, not branch interconnection. DMVPN (option B) is designed for public internet connectivity and requires GRE tunnels that add overhead; multicast support is possible but complex and DMVPN is not optimized for private MPLS. Standard IKEv2 site-to-site VTIs (option D) create point-to-point tunnels that do not natively preserve multicast across an MPLS core.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/solutions/Enterprise/WAN_and_MAN/GETVPN/GETVPN_DIG.html","label":"Cisco GET VPN Design and Implementation Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An enterprise security team needs a VPN solution for connecting multiple branch offices over a private MPLS WAN. The solution must preserve IP multicast routing across all sites and avoid the overhead of a hub-and-spoke design. Which Cisco VPN technology is specifically designed for this use case?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A SOC analyst suspects that a compromised internal host is performing slow, low-volume data exfiltration by making slightly abnormal connections to external IPs. No signature-based IDS alert has fired. Which Cisco security solution is best suited to detect this threat by analyzing behavioral anomalies in network flow data?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cisco Umbrella performing cloud-based DNS inspection"},{"id":"b","text":"Cisco AMP (Advanced Malware Protection) sandboxing"},{"id":"c","text":"Cisco Stealthwatch (Secure Network Analytics) analyzing NetFlow"},{"id":"d","text":"Cisco ISE posture assessment of the endpoint"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Cisco Stealthwatch (now Secure Network Analytics) is correct. The source material states: 'Stealthwatch / Secure Network Analytics: behavioral anomaly detection from NetFlow.' Stealthwatch ingests NetFlow, IPFIX, and other telemetry from routers and switches to build behavioral baselines; it can detect slow-burn exfiltration, insider threats, and command-and-control callbacks that generate no IDS signature. Umbrella (option A) provides DNS-layer security to block connections to known malicious domains but cannot detect anomalous behavior for destinations not in its threat feed. Cisco AMP (option B) performs file reputation analysis and sandboxing at the endpoint/file level, not network-flow behavioral analytics. ISE posture (option D) validates endpoint compliance (patch level, AV status) at connection time; it does not perform ongoing behavioral traffic analysis.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/collateral/security/stealthwatch/datasheet-c78-739398.html","label":"Cisco Secure Network Analytics (Stealthwatch) Data Sheet"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
