INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An automation engineer wants to deploy consistent configurations across a large fleet of Cisco IOS devices without installing any agent software on the managed devices. The team already uses YAML-based playbooks for their workflows. Which configuration management tool aligns with both of these constraints?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Puppet, using its agent-based Ruby DSL architecture"},{"id":"b","text":"Chef, using its agent-based cookbook model"},{"id":"c","text":"Ansible, using agentless SSH/NETCONF transport with YAML playbooks"},{"id":"d","text":"Terraform, using a declarative state-file approach with HCL"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Ansible: agentless, YAML playbooks, SSH/NETCONF.' This satisfies both constraints — no agent software is required on managed Cisco devices, and playbooks are written in YAML. Puppet (option A) and Chef (option B) are both described as 'agent-based, Ruby DSL,' which violates the agentless requirement. Terraform (option D) is described as 'declarative infrastructure with state file' and uses HCL, not YAML playbooks; it is also primarily an infrastructure provisioning tool rather than a network device configuration management tool.$patch$, $patch$Automation$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/network/user_guide/platform_ios.html","label":"Ansible Network Automation – Cisco IOS Platform Guide"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/network-automation/detail/ansible/","label":"Cisco DevNet – Network Automation with Ansible"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An automation engineer wants to deploy consistent configurations across a large fleet of Cisco IOS devices without installing any agent software on the managed devices. The team already uses YAML-based playbooks for their workflows. Which configuration management tool aligns with both of these constraints?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network operations team needs a high-performance telemetry solution to stream real-time operational data from Cisco routers to an external collector. The solution must support efficient binary encoding and a remote procedure call framework. Which technology from the source material best satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"NETCONF, because it supports streaming subscriptions over SSH"},{"id":"b","text":"gRPC with Protocol Buffers, because it is designed for high-performance RPC and streaming telemetry"},{"id":"c","text":"RESTCONF, because it wraps NETCONF operations over HTTPS for efficient delivery"},{"id":"d","text":"EEM applets, because they can trigger on-device scripts when telemetry thresholds are crossed"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'gRPC: high-performance RPC with Protocol Buffers; used by streaming telemetry.' Protocol Buffers provide compact binary encoding (far more efficient than XML or JSON), and gRPC's streaming capabilities are purpose-built for real-time telemetry data. NETCONF (option A) is XML-based and primarily designed for configuration management, not high-throughput telemetry streaming. RESTCONF (option C) is an HTTPS JSON wrapper around NETCONF/YANG operations — useful for configuration, not optimized for binary streaming. EEM (option D) is an on-device automation tool for event-triggered scripting, not a telemetry collection framework.$patch$, $patch$Automation$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/prog/configuration/1612/b_1612_programmability_cg/model_driven_telemetry.html","label":"Cisco IOS XE Programmability Configuration Guide – Model-Driven Telemetry (gRPC)"},{"url":"https://grpc.io/docs/what-is-grpc/introduction/","label":"gRPC Official Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network operations team needs a high-performance telemetry solution to stream real-time operational data from Cisco routers to an external collector. The solution must support efficient binary encoding and a remote procedure call framework. Which technology from the source material best satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer writes a Python script that uses the Netmiko library to connect to a Cisco IOS-XE switch and push a configuration change. During a code review, a colleague suggests replacing Netmiko with NAPALM. What is the primary architectural advantage of NAPALM over Netmiko for this use case?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"NAPALM provides raw SSH socket access, offering lower latency than Netmiko's abstraction layer."},{"id":"b","text":"NAPALM is a multi-vendor abstraction library, allowing the same API calls to work across different network operating systems without rewriting device-specific logic."},{"id":"c","text":"NAPALM eliminates the need for Python entirely by compiling scripts to native machine code."},{"id":"d","text":"NAPALM integrates directly with Cisco DNA Center's northbound REST API, making it ideal for SD-Access environments."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material describes the Python libraries as follows: 'Netmiko (SSH)' and 'NAPALM (multi-vendor abstraction).' Netmiko is a library focused on SSH connectivity, often requiring device-specific command syntax. NAPALM's defining characteristic is multi-vendor abstraction — it provides a unified API that works across Arista EOS, Cisco IOS/NX-OS/IOS-XR, Juniper JunOS, and others, so engineers do not need to rewrite logic per platform. Option A is incorrect — NAPALM adds an abstraction layer, it does not provide lower-level raw socket access (Paramiko, also listed in the source, is the raw SSH library). Option C is false; NAPALM is a Python library. Option D incorrectly conflates NAPALM with Cisco DNA Center APIs, which are separate REST-based integrations mentioned independently in the source.$patch$, $patch$Automation$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://napalm.readthedocs.io/en/latest/support/index.html","label":"NAPALM Official Documentation – Supported Drivers"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/learning/tracks/devnet-express-network-fund/network-automation-with-python/dnav3-301/step/1","label":"Cisco DevNet – Python Libraries for Network Automation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer writes a Python script that uses the Netmiko library to connect to a Cisco IOS-XE switch and push a configuration change. During a code review, a colleague suggests replacing Netmiko with NAPALM. What is the primary architectural advantage of NAPALM over Netmiko for this use case?$patch$);

