INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network architect is designing a large enterprise campus network that must support thousands of endpoints across multiple buildings. The design requires a dedicated layer for high-speed packet switching between distribution blocks, with no routing policy decisions made at that layer. Which campus network architecture model BEST satisfies this requirement, and which layer is being described?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Two-tier (collapsed core) model; the collapsed core/distribution layer handles both high-speed switching and policy decisions."},{"id":"b","text":"Three-tier (campus) model; the core layer is dedicated to high-speed packet switching between distribution blocks with minimal policy enforcement."},{"id":"c","text":"Three-tier (campus) model; the distribution layer is responsible for high-speed switching between access blocks and applies all routing policy."},{"id":"d","text":"SD-Access fabric model; the underlay IS-IS layer performs high-speed switching and replaces the need for a discrete core tier."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that the three-tier (campus) architecture consists of access → distribution → core layers and is designed for large enterprises. The core layer's role is high-speed packet switching between distribution blocks — it is intentionally kept lean and free of complex policy decisions (such as ACLs or QoS classification) so that forwarding performance is maximized. Option A is incorrect because the two-tier collapsed core model merges the core and distribution layers, making it suitable for small networks and inherently combining policy and switching functions. Option C is incorrect because it misidentifies the distribution layer as the high-speed transit layer; distribution is where policy (routing, filtering, summarization) is applied, not where raw switching speed is the sole objective. Option D is incorrect because SD-Access uses a routed IS-IS underlay, but this does not eliminate discrete architectural tiers in a large campus — and the question's requirement maps precisely to the classical three-tier core definition provided in the source material.$patch$, $patch$Architecture$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/solutions/CVD/Campus/cisco-campus-lan-wlan-design-guide.html","label":"Cisco - Campus LAN and Wireless LAN Design Guide (Three-Tier Architecture)"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccnp-and-ccie-enterprise-core-encor-350-401-official-9780138216764","label":"Cisco ENCOR 350-401 Official Cert Guide – Architecture Domain"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network architect is designing a large enterprise campus network that must support thousands of endpoints across multiple buildings. The design requires a dedicated layer for high-speed packet switching between distribution blocks, with no routing policy decisions made at that layer. Which campus network architecture model BEST satisfies this requirement, and which layer is being described?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is evaluating first-hop redundancy protocols (FHRPs) for a new enterprise distribution layer. The primary requirements are: (1) the solution must be an open standard supported across multi-vendor devices, and (2) the active gateway must be elected using the highest priority, with ties broken by the highest IP address. Which FHRP meets BOTH requirements, and what multicast address does it use for router communications?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"HSRP version 2; it uses multicast address 224.0.0.102 and is an IEEE open standard."},{"id":"b","text":"GLBP; it uses multicast address 224.0.0.102, supports multi-vendor environments, and elects an Active Virtual Gateway by highest priority."},{"id":"c","text":"VRRP; it uses multicast address 224.0.0.18, is an open standard (RFC-based), and elects the Master router by highest priority with highest IP address as tiebreaker."},{"id":"d","text":"HSRP version 1; it uses multicast address 224.0.0.2, is an open standard, and elects an active router by highest priority then highest IP address."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly identifies VRRP as the 'open standard' FHRP (compared to HSRP and GLBP, which are described as 'Cisco proprietary'), and states it uses multicast address 224.0.0.18 for router communications. VRRP (defined in RFC 3768/5798) elects a Master router based on the highest priority value, with the highest IP address serving as a tiebreaker — satisfying both stated requirements. Option A is incorrect on two counts: HSRPv2 uses multicast 224.0.0.102 correctly per the source, but HSRP is explicitly called out as 'Cisco proprietary,' not an open standard. Option B is incorrect because GLBP is also identified in the source as 'Cisco proprietary' and its primary differentiator is load balancing across Active Virtual Forwarders (AVFs), not multi-vendor support. Option D is incorrect because HSRPv1 uses multicast 224.0.0.2 (correct per source), but HSRP is Cisco proprietary — directly contradicting the multi-vendor open-standard requirement.$patch$, $patch$Architecture$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5798","label":"RFC 5798 – Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol (VRRP) Version 3"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipapp_fhrp/configuration/xe-16/fhp-xe-16-book/fhp-vrrp.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring VRRP (First Hop Redundancy Protocols)"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccnp-and-ccie-enterprise-core-encor-350-401-official-9780138216764","label":"Cisco ENCOR 350-401 Official Cert Guide – Architecture Domain"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is evaluating first-hop redundancy protocols (FHRPs) for a new enterprise distribution layer. The primary requirements are: (1) the solution must be an open standard supported across multi-vendor devices, and (2) the active gateway must be elected using the highest priority, with ties broken by the highest IP address. Which FHRP meets BOTH requirements, and what multicast address does it use for router communications?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is designing a multi-tenant enterprise WAN solution on a single physical Cisco router. The requirement is that each tenant must have completely isolated routing tables, with the ability to selectively share specific routes between tenants when needed. Which technology directly satisfies both requirements on a single device?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"VXLAN with a unique 24-bit VNI per tenant"},{"id":"b","text":"VRF with route-target import/export for route leaking"},{"id":"c","text":"GRE tunnels with per-tenant tunnel interfaces"},{"id":"d","text":"DMVPN Phase 2 with per-tenant NHRP mappings"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states explicitly: 'VRF (Virtual Routing and Forwarding): Multiple routing tables on the same device; route leaking via route-target import/export. Used for multi-tenancy on a single physical router.' VRF directly provides isolated routing table instances per tenant on a single device, while the route-target import/export mechanism enables controlled, selective route leaking between VRFs — satisfying both stated requirements. Option A (VXLAN/VNI) is a Layer 2 overlay technology primarily used for data-center fabric segmentation and does not itself provide per-tenant routing table isolation on a router. Option C (GRE tunnels) creates point-to-point logical links but does not inherently maintain separate routing tables or enforce tenant isolation at the routing level. Option D (DMVPN Phase 2) is a WAN overlay technology for spoke-to-spoke communication and relies on NHRP for next-hop resolution, but does not address multi-tenant routing table separation on a single device.$patch$, $patch$Virtualization$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/mp_l3_vpns/configuration/xe-17/mp-l3-vpns-xe-17-book/mp-bgp-mpls-vpn.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring Virtual Routing and Forwarding (VRF)"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/encor-exam-topics","label":"Cisco ENCOR (350-401) Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is designing a multi-tenant enterprise WAN solution on a single physical Cisco router. The requirement is that each tenant must have completely isolated routing tables, with the ability to selectively share specific routes between tenants when needed. Which technology directly satisfies both requirements on a single device?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network architect is evaluating tunneling protocols for a new overlay deployment. The solution must support dynamic spoke-to-spoke tunnel establishment without requiring pre-configured static tunnel endpoints between every spoke pair, and it must use next-hop resolution to map overlay addresses to underlay transport addresses. Which combination of technologies, as described in the ENCOR Virtualization domain, fulfills both requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"IPsec in tunnel mode with IKEv2 for every spoke-to-spoke pair"},{"id":"b","text":"DMVPN using mGRE tunnels with NHRP for next-hop resolution"},{"id":"c","text":"VXLAN with a 24-bit VNI providing MAC-in-UDP encapsulation"},{"id":"d","text":"LISP separating EID from RLOC for endpoint mobility"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'GRE: simple IP-in-IP tunneling; multipoint GRE (mGRE) used by DMVPN' and 'DMVPN: NHRP for next-hop resolution; phase 1 (hub-spoke), phase 2 (spoke-to-spoke), phase 3 (NHRP redirect).' DMVPN leverages mGRE, which allows a single tunnel interface to accept connections from multiple dynamic peers without pre-configured point-to-point tunnel entries. NHRP (Next Hop Resolution Protocol) dynamically resolves the underlay (physical) IP address of spoke routers, enabling on-demand spoke-to-spoke tunnels — precisely the two requirements stated. Option A (IPsec tunnel mode with IKEv2) provides encryption and authentication but requires static or pre-negotiated peer definitions for every spoke-to-spoke pair; it does not inherently provide dynamic next-hop resolution. Option C (VXLAN) is a MAC-in-UDP data-center overlay technology with a 24-bit VNI for segmentation; it is not designed for WAN spoke-to-spoke dynamic tunneling with next-hop resolution. Option D (LISP) separates the Endpoint Identifier (EID) from the Routing Locator (RLOC) and is used in SD-Access fabric overlays for endpoint mobility, not for dynamic WAN spoke-to-spoke tunnel establishment.$patch$, $patch$Virtualization$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_conn_dmvpn/configuration/xe-17/sec-conn-dmvpn-xe-17-book/sec-conn-dmvpn-dmvpn.html","label":"Cisco - DMVPN Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security-vpn/dynamic-multipoint-vpn-dmvpn/111976-dmvpn-config-guide-00.html","label":"Cisco - NHRP for DMVPN"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/encor-exam-topics","label":"Cisco ENCOR (350-401) Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network architect is evaluating tunneling protocols for a new overlay deployment. The solution must support dynamic spoke-to-spoke tunnel establishment without requiring pre-configured static tunnel endpoints between every spoke pair, and it must use next-hop resolution to map overlay addresses to underlay transport addresses. Which combination of technologies, as described in the ENCOR Virtualization domain, fulfills both requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer needs to mirror traffic from a distribution-layer switch to an analysis workstation connected to a different switch across the campus network, but the two devices are separated by multiple Layer 2 hops. Which port mirroring technology should the engineer implement to accomplish this without requiring a routed path between the source and destination?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"SPAN (Switched Port Analyzer) configured locally on the distribution switch"},{"id":"b","text":"RSPAN (Remote SPAN) using a dedicated VLAN to carry mirrored traffic across the Layer 2 domain"},{"id":"c","text":"ERSPAN (Encapsulated Remote SPAN) encapsulating mirrored traffic in GRE tunnels across a Layer 3 network"},{"id":"d","text":"EPC (Embedded Packet Capture) exporting pcap files to a TFTP server reachable via the management network"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'SPAN (Switched Port Analyzer): local mirror; RSPAN: remote across VLAN; ERSPAN: across L3 via GRE.' Because the source and destination switches are separated by multiple Layer 2 hops but there is no mention of a routed (Layer 3) path, RSPAN is the correct choice — it uses a dedicated transport VLAN to carry mirrored frames across the Layer 2 domain to a remote destination switch. SPAN (option a) is ruled out because it only works locally on a single switch. ERSPAN (option c) is incorrect here because ERSPAN requires a Layer 3 routed path and uses GRE encapsulation — the scenario explicitly describes a Layer 2 multi-hop topology with no routed path. EPC (option d) is an on-device capture mechanism that writes to local memory or a file server; it does not mirror live traffic to an analysis workstation in real time.$patch$, $patch$Network Assurance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/lanswitch/configuration/xe-16/lanswitch-xe-16-book/lsw-span-rspan-erspan.html","label":"Cisco IOS XE Embedded Packet Capture and SPAN/RSPAN/ERSPAN Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccnp-enterprise-core-encor-350-401-official-cert-guide-9780135768624","label":"Cisco CCNP Enterprise Core ENCOR 350-401 Official Cert Guide — Network Assurance Chapter"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer needs to mirror traffic from a distribution-layer switch to an analysis workstation connected to a different switch across the campus network, but the two devices are separated by multiple Layer 2 hops. Which port mirroring technology should the engineer implement to accomplish this without requiring a routed path between the source and destination?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineer is configuring SNMPv3 on a Cisco IOS XE router and requires both message integrity verification and encryption of the SNMP payload to protect sensitive MIB data in transit. The engineer also wants the managed device to send unsolicited notifications to the NMS, but does NOT require the NMS to acknowledge receipt of those notifications. Which combination of SNMPv3 security level and notification type satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Security level: authNoPriv; Notification type: Informs"},{"id":"b","text":"Security level: authPriv; Notification type: Traps"},{"id":"c","text":"Security level: authPriv; Notification type: Informs"},{"id":"d","text":"Security level: noAuthNoPriv; Notification type: Traps"},{"id":"e","text":"Security level: authNoPriv; Notification type: Traps"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material provides two directly applicable passages: (1) 'SNMPv2c (community string, plaintext) vs SNMPv3 (auth+priv, USM)' — SNMPv3 supports three security levels: noAuthNoPriv (neither authentication nor privacy), authNoPriv (authentication only, no encryption), and authPriv (authentication + encryption/privacy). Because the requirement is for both integrity AND encryption, authPriv is mandatory. (2) 'Traps (unsolicited) vs informs (acknowledged)' — The requirement is for unsolicited notifications WITHOUT requiring acknowledgement from the NMS. Traps are unsolicited and unacknowledged; Informs are acknowledged by the NMS. Therefore the correct combination is authPriv + Traps (option b). Option a is wrong because authNoPriv provides no encryption and Informs require NMS acknowledgement. Option c is wrong because Informs require acknowledgement, violating the stated requirement. Option d is wrong because noAuthNoPriv provides neither integrity nor encryption. Option e is wrong because authNoPriv lacks payload encryption.$patch$, $patch$Network Assurance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/snmp/configuration/xe-16/snmp-xe-16-book/nm-snmp-cfg-snmp-support.html","label":"Cisco IOS XE SNMP Configuration Guide — Configuring SNMP Support"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3411","label":"RFC 3411 — An Architecture for Describing SNMP Management Frameworks (SNMPv3 Security Models)"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccnp-enterprise-core-encor-350-401-official-cert-guide-9780135768624","label":"Cisco CCNP Enterprise Core ENCOR 350-401 Official Cert Guide — Network Assurance Chapter"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineer is configuring SNMPv3 on a Cisco IOS XE router and requires both message integrity verification and encryption of the SNMP payload to protect sensitive MIB data in transit. The engineer also wants the managed device to send unsolicited notifications to the NMS, but does NOT require the NMS to acknowledge receipt of those notifications. Which combination of SNMPv3 security level and notification type satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer needs to implement a solution that encrypts the entire payload of AAA packets, supports per-command authorization, and uses TCP as its transport protocol. Which AAA protocol best satisfies all three requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"RADIUS (UDP/1812)"},{"id":"b","text":"TACACS+ (TCP/49)"},{"id":"c","text":"RADIUS (UDP/1813)"},{"id":"d","text":"Diameter (TCP/3868)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material: 'TACACS+ (TCP/49, encrypts whole payload, command authorization) vs RADIUS (UDP/1812/1813, encrypts only password).' TACACS+ is the only protocol listed that satisfies all three requirements: it uses TCP port 49 for reliable transport, encrypts the entire AAA payload (not just the password), and supports granular per-command authorization — a critical feature for privileged access control. RADIUS uses UDP and only encrypts the password field in Access-Request packets, making it unsuitable when full payload encryption and command-level authorization are required. Diameter is a RADIUS evolution used in service-provider and mobile networks but is not a standard Cisco enterprise device AAA protocol for command authorization.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security-vpn/remote-authentication-dial-in-user-service-radius/13838-10.html","label":"Cisco: TACACS+ and RADIUS Comparison"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccnp-and-ccie-enterprise-core-encor-350-401-official-9780138216764","label":"Cisco ENCOR 350-401 Official Cert Guide – AAA Protocols"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '350-401-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer needs to implement a solution that encrypts the entire payload of AAA packets, supports per-command authorization, and uses TCP as its transport protocol. Which AAA protocol best satisfies all three requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An enterprise is deploying 802.1X port-based authentication on its access layer switches. During the authentication exchange, which device acts as the authenticator, relaying EAP messages between the supplicant and the authentication server?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The end-user host (supplicant)"},{"id":"b","text":"The Cisco Identity Services Engine (ISE)"},{"id":"c","text":"The access layer switch or wireless access point"},{"id":"d","text":"The RADIUS proxy server upstream of ISE"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly defines the 802.1X three-party model: 'supplicant (host) – authenticator (switch/AP) – auth server (ISE/RADIUS).' The access layer switch (or wireless AP) is the authenticator. It enforces port access control and acts as the EAP relay — encapsulating EAP frames from the supplicant into RADIUS packets destined for the authentication server (ISE). The supplicant is the end-user device seeking access; ISE is the authentication server that makes the pass/fail decision; a RADIUS proxy is an optional intermediary and is not the authenticator. Confusing the authenticator with the authentication server is a common misconception on this exam domain.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/sec/b_179_sec_9300_cg/configuring_ieee_802_1x_port_based_authentication.html","label":"Cisco: 802.1X Port-Based Authentication Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/security/ise/3-2/admin_guide/b_ise_admin_3_2/b_ISE_admin_32_secure_wired_access.html","label":"Cisco ISE – 802.1X Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
